description:
In lichen_l2_enable() disable path at lines 1251-1266:
```c
k_mutex_lock(&tx_mutex, K_FOREVER);
if (k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_MSEC(100)) != 0) {
    LOG_ERR(...);
    atomic_set(&link_ctx_initialized, 0);
    k_mutex_unlock(&tx_mutex);
    return -EBUSY;
}
atomic_set(&link_ctx_initialized, 0);
lichen_link_cleanup(&link_ctx);
...
```

If the rx_mutex lock times out (line 1252), the code:
1. Sets link_ctx_initialized = 0 (line 1263)
2. Returns -EBUSY without calling lichen_link_cleanup()

This means link_ctx is NOT cleaned up. It still contains:
- Potentially valid link_key
- Sequence number state
- Other context

The next enable() will see link_ctx_initialized == 0 and call lichen_link_init() which will re-initialize link_ctx. But lichen_link_init() may not zero all fields if it assumes the struct was previously clean.

Looking at line 1082 in the enable path:
```c
secure_zero(&link_ctx, sizeof(link_ctx));
lichen_link_init(&link_ctx, eui64_copy);
```

The enable path does call secure_zero before init. So stale data will be cleared.

HOWEVER: The comment at lines 1258-1262 acknowledges this:
'This ensures the next enable() will re-initialize link_ctx rather than use stale state.'

And the enable path at lines 1081-1083 does secure_zero(&link_ctx) before lichen_link_init(). So the stale key material WILL be cleared on next enable.

NO BUG - the recovery path handles this correctly.
